# Ohms Law

Ohm's Law states that the [voltage](20220318120826-voltage.md) accross a [conductor](20220408103508-conductor.md) is **directly proportional** to the [current](20220408104411-current.md) flowing through it, provided all physical conditions and temperature remain constant.
![2b1f2ebd59623edef6c2e5186f89b21e](data:image/png;base64,)
$$V=IR$$

Ohm's Law can be represented using the [20220408122658 I-V Curve.md](20220408122658-i-v-curve.md)

## Applications of Ohm's Law

1. Determine the [Voltage](20220318120826-voltage.md), [Resistance](20220408115601-resistance.md), or [Current](20220408104411-current.md) of an electric circuit.
2. To maintain the desired [Voltage](20220318120826-voltage.md) drop accross the electric components.

## Limitations of Ohm's Law

1. Not applicable for unilateral electrical elements like [diodes](20220221170726-diode.md) and [transistors](20220225122049-transistor.md) as they allow the current to flow through one direction only.
2. For non-linear electrical elements with parameters like [capacitance](Capacitance), [resistance](20220408115601-resistance.md). The [Voltage](20220318120826-voltage.md) and [Current](20220408104411-current.md) won't be constant with respect to time, making it difficult to use Ohm's Law.
   1. E.g. [Semiconductors](20220225130808-semiconductor.md) are [nonlinear devices](20220408122337-nonlinear-device.md) and are non-ohmic conductors

## Examples

> For the following circuit, determine the value of current $I$ with unit $mA$.
> ![b1d80f5d23cb39f5605983b21a8944db](data:image/png;base64,)

$$
I=\frac{5V}{200\Omega}=0.025A=25mA
$$

## Exclusive Cases

### Temperature is Not Constant

Certain components incresases in temperature when current is increased.

> [!example]
> The temperature of the filament of a light bulb rises as it current increases.
